WEBVTT

00:09.792 --> 00:11.837
Curbside only.

00:11.881 --> 00:15.058
If you know what you're
looking for, we can provide.

00:15.102 --> 00:16.668
It's just the way
it works for me.

00:16.712 --> 00:18.670
- But you're not open.
- Not for browsing, no.

00:18.714 --> 00:20.194
Just for curbside.

00:20.237 --> 00:22.065
You really don't want
to do that, huh?

00:22.109 --> 00:23.458
I don't want people in here.

00:23.501 --> 00:25.155
- Okay.
- It's a place

00:25.199 --> 00:27.027
where the virus can catch.

00:29.464 --> 00:32.815
Not for coming in.
Just for curbside.

00:32.858 --> 00:35.731
If you know what you're
looking for, we might have it.

00:35.774 --> 00:37.472
If you wanna look
on the website,

00:37.515 --> 00:39.300
we have lots of pictures
of the books.

00:39.343 --> 00:41.084
But we're not
letting anyone in.

00:41.128 --> 00:44.000
Even you.
Man is not alone.

00:44.044 --> 00:45.871
I thought you said "Nan."

00:45.915 --> 00:50.006
I thought it was like...
a teenager book.

00:50.050 --> 00:52.269
It's called,
"The Pull of the Stars."

00:56.491 --> 00:59.972
- All right.
- And then some other stuff.

01:00.016 --> 01:02.192
Uh, Judaica?

01:02.236 --> 01:04.281
Can I recommend
something there?

01:04.325 --> 01:05.630
- All right.
- Okay, hold on.

01:05.674 --> 01:07.719
'Cause I got somebody
at the door.

01:07.763 --> 01:09.156
Let me ask him what he wants,
and I'll be right back.

01:09.199 --> 01:10.809
- Hi.
- Hi.

01:10.853 --> 01:12.768
So you're not
letting folks in...

01:12.811 --> 01:15.684
- No, no browsing inside.
- Oh, that's a shame.

01:15.727 --> 01:17.773
I know. I know.
I apologize.

01:17.816 --> 01:19.296
No, that's all right.
Are you Matt?

01:19.340 --> 01:21.037
- Yeah.
- Well I'm glad

01:21.081 --> 01:23.387
- The Bookstore's healthy.
- Thank you. Thank you.

01:23.431 --> 01:26.956
I... yeah, so,
is there a place online...

01:26.999 --> 01:29.567
The Bookstore...
The Bookstore website,

01:29.611 --> 01:31.265
you can browse.
And we have pictures

01:31.308 --> 01:33.876
of a lot of the books
on the website.

01:33.919 --> 01:35.791
So you can't order
on the website,

01:35.834 --> 01:38.402
but you can call me
or email me.

01:38.446 --> 01:40.056
Okay, perfect,
thank you very much.

01:40.100 --> 01:41.492
- What's your name?
- I'm Alex.

01:41.536 --> 01:43.146
I'm a TV writer from LA.

01:43.190 --> 01:44.887
And a couple
of my friends are like,

01:44.930 --> 01:46.236
if you go out there you have
to go this bookstore.

01:46.280 --> 01:47.933
Right.
Yeah, yeah.

01:47.977 --> 01:49.413
Glad to see you're open
a little bit.

01:49.457 --> 01:50.719
- Right.
- But thank you...

01:50.762 --> 01:52.155
How long are you here for?

01:52.199 --> 01:53.983
About another week
and a half.

01:54.026 --> 01:55.941
- Okay, so we'll see you again.
- A hundred percent.

01:55.985 --> 01:57.856
Good, thanks, man.

01:57.900 --> 02:00.207
Okay,
so... um...

02:01.686 --> 02:04.124
[distant voice on phone]

02:15.526 --> 02:17.963
New nonfiction?

02:18.007 --> 02:19.313
Okay...

02:20.966 --> 02:22.272
Right.

02:26.189 --> 02:28.583
Okay, hold on one second,
'cause I'm... getting

02:28.626 --> 02:31.455
a delivery, and I've got
to get him in and out.

02:35.459 --> 02:36.939
I've got one more
for you, sir.

02:36.982 --> 02:38.288
Thank you, man.

02:38.332 --> 02:40.247
It's just really hard.

02:40.290 --> 02:44.207
People go through hard times.

02:44.251 --> 02:47.906
It's just, it's like...
it's so boring.

02:47.950 --> 02:50.518
It's so different.

02:50.561 --> 02:52.172
From everything.

02:55.262 --> 02:57.394
[phone ringing]

02:58.656 --> 03:00.876
[laughing]

03:00.919 --> 03:03.357
[phone ringing]

03:03.400 --> 03:05.097
Hello, Bookstore.

03:05.141 --> 03:07.665
[soft guitar]

03:07.709 --> 03:10.059
[chuckling]
Okay, whatcha lookin' for?

03:17.240 --> 03:20.417
The first line is,
"I love autumn.

03:20.461 --> 03:22.985
That time of year agrees
well with memories."

03:50.317 --> 03:52.362
Somebody's gotta
put them away.

03:52.406 --> 03:54.364
And when... you do this,

03:54.408 --> 03:56.192
When you're the one
whose putting the books away,

03:56.236 --> 03:57.976
you see... everything.

03:58.020 --> 04:00.631
You see...
what you have room for.

04:00.675 --> 04:02.894
Then...

04:02.938 --> 04:04.940
sometimes, then
somebody comes in

04:04.983 --> 04:08.248
later that day,
and you have something

04:08.291 --> 04:11.207
very, you know...

04:11.251 --> 04:13.992
recent in your memory
of a book.

04:14.036 --> 04:16.343
"Oh, I have
just the one for you."

04:16.386 --> 04:18.258
It's so much fun to do that.

04:18.301 --> 04:20.738
[chuckling]

04:20.782 --> 04:22.523
The whole thing is,
it's so much fun.

04:31.053 --> 04:34.056
Hello.
Help with anything?

04:34.099 --> 04:36.145
[woman] Just looking.
It's-- you know,

04:36.188 --> 04:38.234
- it's like a candy store.
- It is a candy store.

04:38.278 --> 04:40.367
Just, you know...
are your hands clean?

04:40.410 --> 04:42.543
[chuckling]

04:42.586 --> 04:44.806
The wine bar is open.

04:44.849 --> 04:46.721
And our motto is,
you can't drink all day

04:46.764 --> 04:48.940
unless you start
in the morning.

04:48.984 --> 04:51.987
- So...
- I'm too old for that.

04:52.030 --> 04:53.249
- [chuckling] Oh.
- I remember doing that.

04:53.293 --> 04:56.034
- All right then.
- A long time ago.

04:56.078 --> 04:58.080
- I-- now I remember you.
- It's always like,

04:58.123 --> 05:00.082
if you start,
you gotta keep going.

05:00.125 --> 05:01.692
Otherwise you'll fall asleep.

05:07.394 --> 05:10.048
Died in 1988.

05:10.092 --> 05:12.181
I remember her stuff though.

05:14.792 --> 05:16.620
A biography
of Mary Cassatt, right.

05:18.143 --> 05:20.407
And a diary.
She did a diary.

05:20.450 --> 05:21.799
Two memoirs.

05:24.149 --> 05:27.675
People walk in,
and they have, you know...

05:27.718 --> 05:30.199
all the various aspects
of their lives.

05:30.242 --> 05:33.028
And... And there's
a book for everyone.

05:33.071 --> 05:35.683
- [laughing]
- True.

05:35.726 --> 05:38.381
I got a book for you.

05:38.425 --> 05:39.904
[woman] How about this one?
This one was really good.

05:39.948 --> 05:41.166
- You loved this one.
- Yeah, I did love

05:41.210 --> 05:42.907
- that one.
- This is great.

05:42.951 --> 05:44.387
A woman came in the store,
and she said,

05:44.431 --> 05:46.215
"Do you have
'The Secret Life of Trees'?"

05:46.258 --> 05:47.956
And I do,
it's down here

05:47.999 --> 05:49.305
in the nature section,
so I said,

05:49.349 --> 05:51.176
did you read
"The Overstory"?

05:51.220 --> 05:53.396
And she said, "Oh, I thought
it was contrived."

05:53.440 --> 05:54.832
Fine, you know, that's,
everybody, you can...

05:54.876 --> 05:56.268
- Right.
- ...have your own opinion.

05:56.312 --> 05:58.140
- Right. Right.
- So... I get down here,

05:58.183 --> 06:00.447
and I get her book.
And I have to get down

06:00.490 --> 06:02.100
on my knee
to get the book.

06:02.144 --> 06:03.798
And I get it,
and I hand it to her,

06:03.841 --> 06:06.322
and she says, "Thank you."

06:06.366 --> 06:07.671
And then I held out
my hand like this,

06:07.715 --> 06:09.369
- and I said...
- Help me up.

06:09.412 --> 06:10.935
- Are you gonna help me up?
- Oh, I thought you were

06:10.979 --> 06:12.589
- gonna propose.
- Just, are you gonna

06:12.633 --> 06:14.678
help me up? And she says,
"That's your problem."

06:14.722 --> 06:16.767
Oh! She... Okay!

06:16.811 --> 06:19.161
And it started to rain.

06:19.204 --> 06:23.165
And she knew that she probably
should seek shelter.

06:23.208 --> 06:25.428
- Yeah.
- But she didn't wanna leave.

06:25.472 --> 06:26.647
The forest was just
so beautiful in the rain.

06:26.690 --> 06:28.692
- Yeah.
- And then she...

06:28.736 --> 06:31.216
hunkered down under a...

06:31.260 --> 06:32.783
the trunk of a tree
that had fallen.

06:32.827 --> 06:34.959
And underneath the tree...

06:35.003 --> 06:36.744
underneath,
in that little hollow,

06:36.787 --> 06:39.442
I saw the moss growing.

06:39.486 --> 06:40.922
[woman] Wow...

06:43.185 --> 06:45.361
[man] Okay,
thank you, okay.

06:48.538 --> 06:51.759
- Hello there, Matthew.
- No, no, no...

06:51.802 --> 06:53.456
Sneaking behind the desk where
I'm never ever supposed to go.

06:53.500 --> 06:55.197
Oh, my goodness-- oh.

06:55.240 --> 06:59.419
"Why do I remember you
as a singing bird?

06:59.462 --> 07:01.682
[laughter]

07:01.725 --> 07:03.945
"My heart is warm
with the friends I make.

07:03.988 --> 07:06.687
And better friends
I'll not be knowing.

07:06.730 --> 07:09.124
But there isn't a train
I wouldn't take.

07:09.167 --> 07:11.039
No matter where it's going."

07:13.215 --> 07:15.565
"Travel,"
by Edna St. Vincent Millay.

07:19.526 --> 07:21.484
I should be able to do
better than this.

07:21.528 --> 07:24.139
I should be able to...
let's say switch,

07:24.182 --> 07:28.186
um, the Coates
and the Zadie Smith.

07:28.230 --> 07:30.101
Although, I don't want
that green one over here

07:30.145 --> 07:31.886
because there's
a green one over here.

07:31.929 --> 07:33.627
So I'll move this green one
over here a little bit,

07:33.670 --> 07:34.889
just like so.

07:36.368 --> 07:38.893
And everything is better.

07:38.936 --> 07:42.331
"Topeka School" is larger,
and I don't-- I want

07:42.374 --> 07:44.376
only small books
in the front here.

07:44.420 --> 07:48.206
So, like
the Edna O'Brien maybe.

07:48.250 --> 07:50.992
But what you lose there is
that it's not face out

07:51.035 --> 07:53.777
as soon as you walk in.
Here's the Crowley.

07:53.821 --> 07:56.258
I'll put the Crowley over here.

07:56.301 --> 07:58.826
Because I can tell people
about the Crowley.

07:58.869 --> 08:00.523
Oh, this came in
today, oh, good.

08:00.567 --> 08:03.613
And we got the
"Charlie the... Tramp."

08:03.657 --> 08:04.875
And "Harvey's Hideout."

08:07.878 --> 08:09.489
So, would you--
will you call her

08:09.532 --> 08:11.229
and tell her
we got this one in?

08:11.273 --> 08:12.579
- Yeah, absolutely.
- And does she know

08:12.622 --> 08:13.797
that there's
a new one coming also?

08:13.841 --> 08:15.233
Yes.

08:17.627 --> 08:19.237
First American publication.

08:19.281 --> 08:20.761
A young woman.
A married man.

08:20.804 --> 08:23.503
A searing love story.
A masterpiece.

08:23.546 --> 08:26.984
"By Grand Central Station,
I sat down and wept."

08:27.028 --> 08:29.291
I found a copy of this book
in a secondhand store

08:29.334 --> 08:31.032
in Tangiers.

08:31.075 --> 08:32.599
It looked terrific,
but I didn't buy it.

08:32.642 --> 08:34.252
I found another
secondhand copy

08:34.296 --> 08:37.647
in... a bookshop in Paris

08:37.691 --> 08:40.128
when I was traveling
in Africa and Europe.

08:40.171 --> 08:42.304
And, uh, didn't buy it.

08:42.347 --> 08:44.349
And always regretted not
having bought it.

08:44.393 --> 08:47.701
And finally when I bought
The Bookstore in 1976,

08:47.744 --> 08:49.833
this edition was available.

08:49.877 --> 08:53.489
It's a used bookstore
with new books.

08:53.533 --> 08:55.709
That is, the value
of an older book

08:55.752 --> 08:59.582
is... still appreciated.

08:59.626 --> 09:02.019
After college,
when I was in the Navy,

09:02.063 --> 09:04.848
is when I met a guy.

09:04.892 --> 09:08.765
And he turned me on
to Henry Miller.

09:08.809 --> 09:12.769
Yeah, Miller.
Mailer. Kerouac.

09:12.813 --> 09:14.597
Fred Exley.

09:14.641 --> 09:16.643
And I fell in love
with writing.

09:16.686 --> 09:19.471
That's what happened.
I fell in love with writing.

09:19.515 --> 09:20.951
So I understood somehow

09:20.995 --> 09:24.999
that this world of books

09:25.042 --> 09:27.349
was...

09:29.177 --> 09:33.355
fascinating,
it was... just...

09:33.398 --> 09:36.619
it was completely
different from my life.

09:36.663 --> 09:39.753
The world of the stories
that I found in books

09:39.796 --> 09:43.583
was so far away from mine,
it was like,

09:43.626 --> 09:46.847
[whispering]
nobody else knew.

09:46.890 --> 09:50.894
I was the only one who knew
what these stories were.

09:59.729 --> 10:01.513
Let me know if we can help
with anything.

10:03.515 --> 10:05.256
The town has changed.

10:05.300 --> 10:07.781
It is. I mean,
it changes all the time.

10:07.824 --> 10:11.306
I think the social aspect
of it has... weakened.

10:11.349 --> 10:13.438
I miss a lot of the old people.

10:13.482 --> 10:15.745
Like Tony Bar Tony would have
one cast of characters.

10:15.789 --> 10:18.052
You would have your...

10:18.095 --> 10:19.967
- Crowd, yeah.
- ...more of the literary type.

10:20.010 --> 10:22.099
There were a lot
of characters in our town.

10:22.143 --> 10:24.101
"'Well,' said Grandfather,

10:24.145 --> 10:25.886
'Charlie's getting to be
a big boy.'

10:25.929 --> 10:29.280
'Yes.' Grandfather took
a quarter out of his pocket.

10:29.324 --> 10:31.935
'What are you gonna be when
you grow up?' said Grandfather.

10:31.979 --> 10:34.372
'I'm going to be a tramp.'

10:34.416 --> 10:36.592
Grandfather put the quarter
back into his pocket."

10:36.636 --> 10:38.638
[laughing]

10:38.681 --> 10:41.728
- I want to be a tramp.
- You would love this book.

10:41.771 --> 10:44.513
- Are you a secret agent?
- A what?

10:44.556 --> 10:46.950
A secret agent.
No, he is.

10:46.994 --> 10:48.343
- He is.
- Okay.

10:48.386 --> 10:50.737
- No comment.
- [laughter]

10:50.780 --> 10:52.434
Together, we'll take
good pictures,

10:52.477 --> 10:53.870
and we'll get them
published.

10:53.914 --> 10:55.959
But we gotta come up
with a... pen name.

10:56.003 --> 10:58.745
You know, a new name
for the both of our work.

10:58.788 --> 11:01.225
And the name they came up with
was Robert Capa.

11:02.357 --> 11:04.489
So Gerda Taro

11:04.533 --> 11:07.014
and AndrÃ© Friedman were
Robert Capa.

11:07.057 --> 11:08.276
Huh.

11:10.191 --> 11:11.975
You know Russell Hoban
because he wrote

11:12.019 --> 11:13.411
all of the "Bread
and Jam for Frances."

11:13.455 --> 11:14.804
Oh yeah, totally.

11:24.466 --> 11:26.642
Hi.

11:26.686 --> 11:29.645
So, you know, this is...
a book about sibling rivalry.

11:29.689 --> 11:30.907
Oh, perfect.

11:30.951 --> 11:33.736
She comes to her...

11:33.780 --> 11:36.086
to her memory
through literature.

11:36.130 --> 11:37.653
Through the poems.

11:37.697 --> 11:39.742
Through poets.

11:39.786 --> 11:41.744
Through the filter
of the life

11:41.788 --> 11:43.659
- that she lives.
- Okay, okay.

11:43.703 --> 11:45.095
You wanna know how it ends?

11:45.139 --> 11:47.576
[laughing]

11:47.619 --> 11:48.925
I'll just go
with this one, I guess.

11:48.969 --> 11:50.361
- Okay. Great.
- Just get that.

11:55.018 --> 11:57.107
[whistling]

11:57.151 --> 11:59.066
- Hello.
- Well, good afternoon.

11:59.109 --> 12:00.763
Is it afternoon?

12:00.807 --> 12:02.460
- How are you?
- I don't recognize you.

12:02.504 --> 12:05.550
You've got so many mittens
and... scarves and...

12:05.594 --> 12:07.814
- [laughter]
- It's cold.

12:07.857 --> 12:10.381
You're free to the air.
How are you?

12:14.734 --> 12:16.257
[woman] Something
that has been weighing

12:16.300 --> 12:19.216
on my moral conscience is
the number of books

12:19.260 --> 12:22.785
that I order through Amazon
for convenience sake.

12:22.829 --> 12:25.135
And it has occurred to me--
I know, I know.

12:25.179 --> 12:27.224
I said it.
I said it out loud.

12:27.268 --> 12:29.531
It has occurred to me that
not only is this, like,

12:29.574 --> 12:32.273
an environmental catastrophe,

12:32.316 --> 12:34.492
but that, you know,

12:34.536 --> 12:37.191
I could do better in terms
of supporting bookstores.

12:37.234 --> 12:39.193
And I was wondering,
I don't want to be

12:39.236 --> 12:41.673
a pain in the neck either,
but I was wondering

12:41.717 --> 12:44.241
if I let you know
in advance

12:44.285 --> 12:46.678
the books that I need,
could I procure them

12:46.722 --> 12:48.071
- from you?
- Absolutely.

12:48.115 --> 12:50.421
So you're deep...
into "Harry Potter"?

12:50.465 --> 12:52.423
Deep.

12:52.467 --> 12:54.991
I think I... have
a gift for you.

12:55.035 --> 12:57.211
We missed
the "Harry Potter" Halloween.

12:57.254 --> 12:59.909
Can I... find
something for you

12:59.953 --> 13:02.782
- from that event?
- [laughing]

13:02.825 --> 13:05.001
- Is it a magic wand?
- Uh-huh.

13:08.396 --> 13:10.485
[soft guitar]

13:28.764 --> 13:30.766
I couldn't button
my pants today.

13:30.810 --> 13:32.986
[laughing]

13:33.029 --> 13:34.901
So, do you have to go out
and buy all these new clothes?

13:34.944 --> 13:36.772
Not yet.

13:36.816 --> 13:38.556
I'm just gonna put
tank tops over.

13:40.428 --> 13:42.125
This is...

13:42.169 --> 13:43.605
Speaking of
"nourishing the new mother."

13:44.911 --> 13:46.477
Are you--
so you're eating more?

13:46.521 --> 13:48.740
- Yeah.
- Wow.

13:50.960 --> 13:53.049
- Is this your fork?
- It is.

13:53.093 --> 13:55.051
- I'm sorry it's not washed.
- It's fine.

13:55.095 --> 13:56.966
- [laughing]
- I was missing it.

13:59.273 --> 14:00.883
- You want a bag?
- No.

14:00.927 --> 14:02.450
- Okay.
- All right.

14:02.493 --> 14:04.321
- I'll see you tomorrow.
- All right, so,

14:04.365 --> 14:05.801
what's happening is,
so you'll come in tomorrow

14:05.845 --> 14:07.803
and help me out
a little bit-- Sunday,

14:07.847 --> 14:09.761
since I haven't had
a day off in a while,

14:09.805 --> 14:11.546
I'm taking the day off.

14:11.589 --> 14:13.156
- Yeah.
- Cool, all right.

14:13.200 --> 14:14.897
- You go home.
- Okay.

14:14.941 --> 14:16.551
- Say hi to Michael.
- I will. Love you.

14:16.594 --> 14:18.161
Love you too.

14:22.209 --> 14:24.167
"At seven,
I was a soldier.

14:24.211 --> 14:25.734
At nine, a prince.

14:25.777 --> 14:27.214
But now, I'm mostly
at the window

14:27.257 --> 14:28.955
watching
the late afternoon light.

14:28.998 --> 14:30.826
Back then,
it never fell so solemnly

14:30.870 --> 14:32.784
against the side
of my treehouse.

14:32.828 --> 14:34.351
It seems only yesterday,

14:34.395 --> 14:35.918
I used to believe
there was nothing

14:35.962 --> 14:38.747
underneath my skin
but light.

14:38.790 --> 14:41.619
If you cut me,
I could shine."

14:44.622 --> 14:49.889
But it was... after
Sheila died that I was...

14:49.932 --> 14:52.413
that whatever it was
that happened to me

14:52.456 --> 14:57.113
as the survivor,
as the spouse, as the...

14:57.157 --> 14:59.246
whatever guilt you have
as a survivor.

14:59.289 --> 15:02.814
You know, whatever things
you want to do, raising--

15:02.858 --> 15:05.687
realizing that
I'm raising this family,

15:05.730 --> 15:07.297
these children...

15:07.341 --> 15:09.212
just like I was raised
by a single parent

15:09.256 --> 15:11.649
after my--
after I was orphaned.

15:11.693 --> 15:14.261
So I understood
that my kids were orphaned.

15:14.304 --> 15:16.176
They had me,
but they were orphaned.

15:16.219 --> 15:18.482
And... it was just
a combination

15:18.526 --> 15:21.833
of that knowledge,
and that wisdom, and that...

15:21.877 --> 15:25.620
visceral sense of the...

15:25.663 --> 15:27.535
of our lifespan.

15:27.578 --> 15:30.625
[somber piano]

15:43.072 --> 15:44.552
Actually, can we get a bag?

15:44.595 --> 15:46.815
- Of course.
- [chatter]

15:46.858 --> 15:48.121
I'll give you
some bookmarks.

15:48.164 --> 15:49.731
Awesome, thank you.

15:51.472 --> 15:53.300
I don't think people
should ask you

15:53.343 --> 15:56.477
- if you're gonna have kids.
- [laughing]

15:56.520 --> 15:59.523
It's such an intensely
personal question and topic.

16:01.569 --> 16:02.962
Yeah.

16:05.877 --> 16:07.270
The doctor was like...

16:07.314 --> 16:09.490
she couldn't find
the heartbeat at first.

16:09.533 --> 16:11.057
And then she was like,
"Wait-- is it that low?"

16:11.100 --> 16:12.797
She was like, "Oh, my God,
you poor thing.

16:12.841 --> 16:14.190
It's still
sitting this low?

16:14.234 --> 16:15.757
Are you peeing
all the time?"

16:15.800 --> 16:17.237
Whatever.

16:20.283 --> 16:22.111
So, yes, I am.

16:23.634 --> 16:25.071
"A man was
cleaning the attic

16:25.114 --> 16:26.550
of an old house
in New England,

16:26.594 --> 16:27.943
and he found a box
which was full

16:27.987 --> 16:30.076
of tiny pieces of string.

16:30.119 --> 16:31.773
On the lid of the box,
there was

16:31.816 --> 16:33.644
an inscription
in an old hand:

16:33.688 --> 16:36.343
'string too short
to be saved.'"

16:45.526 --> 16:48.746
[soft guitar]

16:56.319 --> 16:58.191
"While the moon
smoothly shifted

16:58.234 --> 17:01.194
the shadows from one side
of Edgewood to the other,

17:01.237 --> 17:02.934
Daily Alice dreamed
that she stood

17:02.978 --> 17:04.719
in a flower starred field,

17:04.762 --> 17:06.503
where on a hill
there grew an oak tree

17:06.547 --> 17:08.331
and a thorn in deep embrace,

17:08.375 --> 17:11.378
their branches
intertwined like fingers.

17:11.421 --> 17:13.075
Far down the hall,
Sophie dreamed there was

17:13.119 --> 17:14.859
a tiny door in her elbow,

17:14.903 --> 17:17.079
open a crack,
through which the wind blew,

17:17.123 --> 17:19.212
blowing on her heart."

17:19.255 --> 17:22.041
"Doctor Drinkwater dreamed
he sat before his typewriter

17:22.084 --> 17:23.999
and wrote this:

17:24.043 --> 17:25.522
'There is an aged,
aged insect

17:25.566 --> 17:27.350
who lives
in a hole in the ground.

17:27.394 --> 17:29.657
One June, he puts on
his summer straw

17:29.700 --> 17:31.789
and takes his pipe and staff

17:31.833 --> 17:33.791
and his lamp
in half his hands,

17:33.835 --> 17:35.489
and follows
the worm in the root

17:35.532 --> 17:37.491
to the stair
that leads up to the door

17:37.534 --> 17:39.884
into blue summer.'

17:39.928 --> 17:42.626
This seemed immensely
significant to him,

17:42.670 --> 17:44.585
but when he awoke,
he wouldn't be able

17:44.628 --> 17:47.849
to remember a word of it,
try hard as he might.

17:47.892 --> 17:50.025
Mother beside him dreamed
her husband wasn't

17:50.069 --> 17:52.941
in his study at all,
but with her in the kitchen,

17:52.984 --> 17:54.638
where she drew
tin cookie sheets

17:54.682 --> 17:56.684
endlessly out of the oven.

17:56.727 --> 17:59.991
The baked things on them
were brown and round,

18:00.035 --> 18:01.819
and when he asked her
what they were,

18:01.863 --> 18:04.126
she said, 'Years.'"

