36:58.041 --> 36:59.565
And the only place
that has them

36:59.608 --> 37:01.567
in the country is
the Gotham Book Mart."

37:01.610 --> 37:02.959
So I walked
into the Gotham Book Mart.

37:03.003 --> 37:04.831
I was not a bookseller.
I was just fresh

37:04.874 --> 37:07.790
out of the United States Navy,

37:07.834 --> 37:12.012
um, and looking
for direction in my life.

37:12.055 --> 37:14.057
And so I walked
into the Gotham Book Mart.

37:14.101 --> 37:17.713
And I think it was
the smell of the wooden floor.

37:17.757 --> 37:20.934
And the smell of the books...

37:20.977 --> 37:23.589
um, that just--
that just-- hi.

37:23.632 --> 37:26.156
That just did me in.
Welcome.

37:28.768 --> 37:31.727
When I think
of the Gotham...

37:31.771 --> 37:34.774
I think that's how it was a...

37:34.817 --> 37:37.646
among all the other things
that it is and was,

37:37.690 --> 37:41.302
it was a, um...

37:41.346 --> 37:46.873
the last of...
the old-time bookstores.

37:46.916 --> 37:49.354
The Gotham Book Mart was
started by Frances Steloff.

37:49.397 --> 37:51.573
A woman in...

37:51.617 --> 37:54.837
she opened it
on January 1st, 1920.

37:54.881 --> 37:57.971
And she... had been
working in books

37:58.014 --> 37:59.538
and department stores
before that.

37:59.581 --> 38:01.844
She was an orphan girl
from Saratoga

38:01.888 --> 38:03.629
and had made her way
to New York.

38:03.672 --> 38:05.892
And now in the late '60s,

38:05.935 --> 38:07.589
early '70s,
by the time I got there,

38:07.633 --> 38:09.374
she was the most famous
bookseller in America.

38:09.417 --> 38:11.289
And she had sold her shop,

38:11.332 --> 38:12.551
but she-- but she still
owned the building.

38:12.594 --> 38:14.248
And she lived upstairs.

38:14.292 --> 38:16.076
And she still came
into work every day.

38:16.119 --> 38:19.471
And I would sit
literally at her knee.

38:19.514 --> 38:21.299
She had a little alcove.

38:21.342 --> 38:24.693
And... so outside was
all of this literature.

38:24.737 --> 38:26.478
Fiction.
All this poetry.

38:26.521 --> 38:28.610
Great poetry.
Film. Theater.

38:28.654 --> 38:30.743
Great stuff, 'cause,
the reason she started

38:30.786 --> 38:33.528
on 52nd Street was...
it was the theater district.

38:33.572 --> 38:36.966
Martha Graham used to come in
and hold her finger,

38:37.010 --> 38:39.229
so Frances could tie
the bow on a gift,

38:39.273 --> 38:41.362
on, you know, a book
that they were gift-wrapping

38:41.406 --> 38:44.060
like... the early,
you know, Christmas days.

38:44.104 --> 38:47.063
Anyway, Frances is, like,
this famous person.

38:47.107 --> 38:48.717
And-- but she didn't
read books.

38:50.110 --> 38:51.633
She had her finger
on the pulse,

38:51.677 --> 38:54.244
but she didn't read books,
and her alcove,

38:54.288 --> 38:56.812
which was probably about
the size of this area here,

38:56.856 --> 38:58.771
where it was
just all the...

38:58.814 --> 39:02.296
um, philosophy
and religion books.

39:02.340 --> 39:05.255
And she was greatly interested
in Eastern religion.

39:05.299 --> 39:07.780
So this was the '60s,
this was the early '70s.

39:07.823 --> 39:09.216
And I'm, like,
the hippie on the staff.

39:09.259 --> 39:12.132
Right? I got...
glazy eyes and, um...

39:12.175 --> 39:17.050
I handled the stock.
So I really learned,

39:17.093 --> 39:19.531
like a young child...

39:19.574 --> 39:23.883
learns through
his or her limbs,

39:23.926 --> 39:25.711
I learned my trade viscerally.

39:27.539 --> 39:29.932
And the shelves in the back

39:29.976 --> 39:34.284
were so deep that
books were double-shelved.

39:34.328 --> 39:36.852
I had to really get
the alphabet down.

39:36.896 --> 39:38.854
You know, somewhere between,

39:38.898 --> 39:44.251
after G-H-I-J-K-M-Mc-Mac...

39:44.294 --> 39:47.646
um, it got confusing to a--
to a young stoner.

39:47.689 --> 39:50.083
I had to deliver
a manuscript

39:50.126 --> 39:52.564
to the people at Scribner's.

39:52.607 --> 39:57.090
And I walked up those stairs
to the Scribner's publishers,

39:57.133 --> 40:00.441
thinking, you know, Fitzgerald
walked up these stairs.

40:00.485 --> 40:03.183
Hemingway walked up
these stairs.

40:03.226 --> 40:05.751
One of my later
favorite writers,

40:05.794 --> 40:07.927
Marjorie Rawlings,
walked up these stairs.

40:07.970 --> 40:09.668
Thomas Wolfe walked up
these stairs.

40:09.711 --> 40:11.931
Edith Wharton, eh...

40:11.974 --> 40:13.585
she probably sat
outside in the car,

40:13.628 --> 40:16.109
and her chauffeur walked up
the stairs.

40:16.152 --> 40:17.850
I don't know...
that's what I want to think.

