44:34.933 --> 44:36.674
I'll try.

44:36.717 --> 44:37.979
All right.
And the other one?

44:38.023 --> 44:39.154
- Is that--
- I'll try.

44:39.198 --> 44:40.460
Okay, great.

44:47.685 --> 44:49.991
[laughing]

44:50.035 --> 44:52.298
- All right.
- Okay.

44:52.341 --> 44:54.430
You've made my day
by buying this book.

44:54.474 --> 44:56.041
Oh, I'm so excited.

44:56.084 --> 44:57.782
I'm going to read it
to my daughter.

44:57.825 --> 44:59.087
- You read it to her.
- And we'll come in

44:59.131 --> 45:00.306
- and tell you.
- Okay, okay.

45:00.349 --> 45:03.613
[whistle blowing]

45:03.657 --> 45:07.095
RX, $29.75.

45:07.139 --> 45:08.401
And wrap it?

45:11.230 --> 45:12.971
Lewis.
Lewis, who?

45:13.014 --> 45:15.103
- We come up every year.
- Yeah, yeah.

45:15.147 --> 45:16.888
You're a rare breed.

45:16.931 --> 45:18.585
You ought to be
stuffed and mounted.

45:20.500 --> 45:22.023
- I think it's wonderful.
- And--

45:22.067 --> 45:23.503
I love this kind of shop.

45:23.546 --> 45:25.287
And I thought to myself...

45:25.331 --> 45:26.811
suddenly,
I had this image

45:26.854 --> 45:29.117
of Len Riggio,

45:29.161 --> 45:31.641
who owned Barnes & Noble
at the time,

45:31.685 --> 45:34.862
and his study,
where he has the heads

45:34.906 --> 45:37.822
of all the independent
booksellers,

45:37.865 --> 45:40.085
stuffed and mounted
on his trophy wall.

45:40.128 --> 45:41.695
[laughing]

45:54.752 --> 45:56.188
And what are you reading now?

45:56.231 --> 45:58.581
Uh, the one
I'm reading now is...

46:01.149 --> 46:03.804
let's see if I have
another copy somewhere.

46:03.848 --> 46:05.806
It's called
"The Girl with a Leica."

46:05.850 --> 46:08.113
- "The Girl with a Leica."
- "Girl with a Leica."

46:08.156 --> 46:10.071
And it's a great story.

46:12.247 --> 46:13.814
Let's go down here

46:13.858 --> 46:15.381
- to the fiction section.
- Okay.

46:15.424 --> 46:16.991
- How have you been?
- I'm good, thank you.

46:17.035 --> 46:18.776
I'm very good, thank you.

46:18.819 --> 46:22.170
I... I'm going
to be a grandpa.

46:22.214 --> 46:23.955
- You're gonna be a grandpa!
- I'm gonna be a grandpa.

46:23.998 --> 46:25.913
Oh, that's the best.
That's the best.

46:25.957 --> 46:27.828
That's the best.
My kids are coming today,

46:27.872 --> 46:29.874
- and I'm so excited.
- For a young person...

46:29.917 --> 46:31.745
for a young person
like us...

46:31.789 --> 46:33.442
Like us,
it's hard to believe.

46:33.486 --> 46:36.837
So, so... this is
one of the best-written books

46:36.881 --> 46:38.621
- I've ever read.
- All right, so maybe

46:38.665 --> 46:40.449
- I'd better buy this one.
- You should buy it.

46:40.493 --> 46:41.929
It took me three days

46:41.973 --> 46:43.322
- to read this book.
- Oh, my God.

46:43.365 --> 46:45.019
My bookmark never
had a chance.

46:45.063 --> 46:47.195
- [laughing]
- I would close it,

46:47.239 --> 46:48.631
and I would open it
right back up.

46:48.675 --> 46:50.242
You could sell me on anything.

46:50.285 --> 46:52.331
These are-- These are...

46:52.374 --> 46:55.987
so well-drawn...

46:56.030 --> 46:58.554
portraits
of a Midwestern family.

46:58.598 --> 47:00.208
He's a great
Midwestern writer.

47:00.252 --> 47:02.080
I have to find-- all right,
I'm going to read these.

47:02.123 --> 47:04.386
- No-no-no, you don't--
- No, I need to.

47:04.430 --> 47:06.911
- It sounds delightful.
- They're so... delicious.

47:06.954 --> 47:09.174
That sounds fabulous.
Okay, this.

47:09.217 --> 47:11.132
And I have to read this.
Thank you so much.

47:11.176 --> 47:13.004
Happy, healthy.
Great to see you.

47:13.047 --> 47:14.875
- Mmm.
- Take care.

47:14.919 --> 47:16.529
- See you again.
- I'll be back

47:16.572 --> 47:18.487
- to discuss these.
- And send me emails also.

47:18.531 --> 47:19.837
My email address is

47:19.880 --> 47:21.186
- on the bookmark.
- Okay.

47:30.760 --> 47:34.764
"And I'd grown from solitude,
blushed when I stumbled,

47:34.808 --> 47:36.941
loved strangers
and bread and butter,

47:36.984 --> 47:39.900
and made long trips through
the rain on my bicycle,

47:39.944 --> 47:42.424
stared wretchedly
through lighted windows,

47:42.468 --> 47:45.906
grinned wryly to think
how little I was understood,

47:45.950 --> 47:48.213
and lived in a state
of raging excitement."

47:49.910 --> 47:51.869
She was 21 years old.

47:51.912 --> 47:54.132
- He was 31.
- Ooh.

47:54.175 --> 47:56.177
He came to
this country illegally,

47:56.221 --> 47:58.788
because by the time
the rest of his family

47:58.832 --> 48:00.703
had emigrated
from Poland and...

48:00.747 --> 48:02.792
What are we looking for?

48:02.836 --> 48:04.142
It's okay.

48:04.185 --> 48:06.013
- Oh, uh...
- I'll take this.

48:06.057 --> 48:07.972
And by the time
he tried to get here,

48:08.015 --> 48:10.017
because he was out wandering
with the Socialists,

48:10.061 --> 48:12.237
and he came back to the house,
and there was a note

48:12.280 --> 48:14.021
on the door that said,
"Gone to America."

48:14.065 --> 48:15.936
So he tried
to come to America,

48:15.980 --> 48:17.677
and-- but the quota
was in effect,

48:17.720 --> 48:19.548
and so he signed on
with the Canadians.

48:19.592 --> 48:21.855
- Oh.
- And-- for free passage

48:21.899 --> 48:23.726
from Hamburg to Montreal.

48:23.770 --> 48:25.163
Oh, wow.
Oh, my God.

48:25.206 --> 48:27.165
So he gets to Montreal,

48:27.208 --> 48:28.818
and he jumps off the ship.

48:28.862 --> 48:30.690
He's not going
to Saskatchewan.

48:30.733 --> 48:32.344
Oh, he does?
He swims to shore?

48:32.387 --> 48:34.912
Yeah, and he--
and he finds his cousin,

48:34.955 --> 48:36.826
who lives in Montreal.

48:36.870 --> 48:38.828
And they-- they stole
a rowboat or something.

48:38.872 --> 48:40.743
And they rode across
the St. Lawrence,

48:40.787 --> 48:43.094
and he came down to New York,
and he moved in

48:43.137 --> 48:45.009
with his parents,
who were already in Brooklyn.

48:45.052 --> 48:46.836
- Wow, great.
- He met my mother

48:46.880 --> 48:48.969
at a high school dance.

48:49.013 --> 48:50.971
He went there,
and she had a date.

48:51.015 --> 48:52.973
And he said,
"I'll take you home."

48:53.017 --> 48:56.977
- He swept her...
- He swept her off her feet.

48:57.021 --> 49:00.763
There are two types
of... of novels.

49:00.807 --> 49:02.983
One that you sit
at home and write.

49:03.027 --> 49:05.246
And one that you tell
other people about

49:05.290 --> 49:07.205
- sitting at a bar.
- Just-- right.

49:07.248 --> 49:09.294
And this is...
I'm just sitting at a bar.

49:09.337 --> 49:11.252
I've been sitting at a bar
for 43 years.

49:14.908 --> 49:16.997
[soft piano]

49:21.088 --> 49:22.611
So, so the other thing
he said was,

49:22.655 --> 49:24.309
if you have
two different editions

49:24.352 --> 49:26.093
of a book...

49:26.137 --> 49:28.400
Like "Joy of Cooking"
was out in a little

49:28.443 --> 49:30.402
mass market paperback,
and then it was out

49:30.445 --> 49:33.971
- in a larger spiral bound.
- That's the one I have.

49:34.014 --> 49:36.799
They had an edition
with spiral bound for a while.

49:36.843 --> 49:38.888
So he said, you know, "Always
get the more expensive one.

49:38.932 --> 49:40.194
You make more money off that."

49:40.238 --> 49:41.848
- Mm-hmm.
- And Rita,

49:41.891 --> 49:44.285
who worked here.
Remember Rita?

49:44.329 --> 49:45.808
- No, I don't remember Rita.
- No, she was

49:45.852 --> 49:47.636
one of my first employees.

49:47.680 --> 49:49.943
She stood up,

49:49.987 --> 49:51.858
stamped her feet,
and she said,

49:51.901 --> 49:54.078
"If Francine Derry
comes in here

49:54.121 --> 49:55.905
looking for
'The Joy of Cooking,'

49:55.949 --> 49:57.472
I don't want to have
to sell her

49:57.516 --> 49:59.083
- a more expensive one."
- A more expensive one.

49:59.126 --> 50:01.041
"She's the one
I buy my underwear from,

50:01.085 --> 50:02.956
and I'm not gonna try

50:03.000 --> 50:04.697
to make
any extra money off her."

50:04.740 --> 50:07.004
And I'll always remember
that that's--

50:07.047 --> 50:09.571
that you don't
just try to make money.

50:09.615 --> 50:12.226
- Yes, yeah.
- And-- And look at me.

50:12.270 --> 50:14.141
I've been
a poor bookseller

50:14.185 --> 50:15.969
all my life.
[laughing]

50:16.013 --> 50:17.536
I tried not to make any money.

50:17.579 --> 50:19.233
[laughing]

50:19.277 --> 50:20.713
But you'll make
some right now because...

50:20.756 --> 50:22.236
- Oh, yeah?
- ...you've got a customer.

50:22.280 --> 50:23.890
Oh, somebody's right there.

50:23.933 --> 50:25.239
- To give you money.
- Okay.

50:30.462 --> 50:33.117
So were the kids all here
this Christmas?

50:33.160 --> 50:34.596
- My kids?
- Yeah.

50:34.640 --> 50:36.816
Yeah, but I'm furious
at my daughter.

50:36.859 --> 50:39.427
- You're furious?
- Yeah.

50:39.471 --> 50:41.081
Don't forget
your bag this time.

50:41.125 --> 50:42.865
- Okay, I won't.
- Okay.

50:45.129 --> 50:46.695
But if I make something nice,

50:46.739 --> 50:49.133
'cause Sam's gonna
come tomorrow,

50:49.176 --> 50:50.699
do you like scallops?

50:50.743 --> 50:52.658
Uh, I do.

50:52.701 --> 50:54.051
- Okay.
- All right.

50:54.094 --> 50:55.791
We'll make some for you too.

50:55.835 --> 50:57.184
All right.

50:59.317 --> 51:01.014
Jim!

51:01.058 --> 51:02.146
I have books here.

51:02.189 --> 51:03.408
- Oh!
- That I...

51:03.451 --> 51:05.453
- [dinging bell]
- ...got a call for

51:05.497 --> 51:07.455
about two months ago.

51:12.069 --> 51:13.853
Maybe I don't.

51:13.896 --> 51:16.029
I remember you ordering
a couple of books.

51:16.073 --> 51:17.639
[man] Do you want me
to pick you up three?

51:17.683 --> 51:19.598
It was a Steve Hamilton book.

51:19.641 --> 51:21.513
And a...

51:21.556 --> 51:23.167
Yes, it was Steve Hamilton.

51:25.430 --> 51:27.606
And Eisler.

51:27.649 --> 51:29.564
- Barry Eisler.
- Barry Eisler?

51:29.608 --> 51:32.741
Maybe like
the pharmaceuticals,

51:32.785 --> 51:34.613
you know, CVS.

51:34.656 --> 51:36.223
You don't pick it up
in two weeks,

51:36.267 --> 51:37.877
they put it
back on the shelf.

51:37.920 --> 51:40.053
I'm gonna look
on my shelf at home.

51:40.097 --> 51:42.795
And see if--
maybe I picked it up.

51:42.838 --> 51:44.971
- I think you might have.
- Bye, Jim.

51:45.014 --> 51:47.321
- I think you might have.
- You think so?

51:47.365 --> 51:49.149
I don't know.
It's all a blur.

51:49.193 --> 51:51.456
Another successful transaction.

51:51.499 --> 51:53.284
[laughing]

51:53.327 --> 51:56.635
He came in,
and he bought it on the 10th.

51:56.678 --> 51:58.985
He must have really
enjoyed the books.

51:59.028 --> 52:01.422
[soft guitar]

52:07.080 --> 52:08.603
"Over the snow,
my creaking feet,

52:08.647 --> 52:12.520
"disturbed the slumbering
village street.

52:12.564 --> 52:15.523
"By profanation
by your leave,

52:15.567 --> 52:19.527
at 10 o'clock
of a winter eve."

52:19.571 --> 52:21.486
I mean, it's fine,
just like...

52:21.529 --> 52:24.184
- Yeah, right.
- But now she has to...

52:24.228 --> 52:25.577
Both places, right.

52:27.187 --> 52:29.320
Pretty-- Pretty cool.

52:29.363 --> 52:31.148
All over--
All over town.

52:31.191 --> 52:33.324
The word is--
the word's getting out.

52:36.109 --> 52:38.459
So-- So,
Tom Stoppard comes in,

52:38.503 --> 52:41.419
and... and he--

52:41.462 --> 52:43.682
he compliments me
on the shop because--

52:43.725 --> 52:46.293
because he found a book that
he didn't think he'd find.

52:46.337 --> 52:48.730
He said, "I like the fact
that you have your...

52:48.774 --> 52:50.515
your biographies
next to your authors."

52:50.558 --> 52:52.299
So there's
a biography of Hemingway

52:52.343 --> 52:53.953
- next to Hemingway's work.
- Oh, really?

52:53.996 --> 52:56.347
So, I said-- I said,
well, I learned...

52:56.390 --> 52:58.827
I learned my trade
at the Gotham Book Mart.

52:58.871 --> 53:00.829
And he said, "Oh...

53:00.873 --> 53:03.180
we shall never see
the likes of that again."

53:03.223 --> 53:05.399
In his deep,
sonorous voice.

53:05.443 --> 53:06.748
Which was my cue to give him

53:06.792 --> 53:08.707
my copy...
a copy of my book,

53:08.750 --> 53:10.622
"My Life
at the Gotham Book Mart."

53:10.665 --> 53:11.927
- Yes, yeah.
- And he looked at it,

53:11.971 --> 53:13.625
and he said,
"May I purchase this?"

53:13.668 --> 53:15.975
I said, certainly.
But you know what,

53:16.018 --> 53:17.759
last night
I found a book for you.

53:17.803 --> 53:19.587
- Yeah?
- On my shelf

53:19.631 --> 53:20.980
that I'm gonna give to you
for your birthday.

53:21.023 --> 53:23.374
- Okay.
- The truth is,

53:23.417 --> 53:26.290
whatever I've learned
in my life...

53:26.333 --> 53:28.379
comes mostly from...

53:30.772 --> 53:32.426
the characters who I've read,

53:32.470 --> 53:34.646
who I've absorbed,
who I relate to,

53:34.689 --> 53:36.256
are the fictional characters.

53:36.300 --> 53:38.215
Fiction is the filter
through which

53:38.258 --> 53:40.913
I see the world.

53:42.262 --> 53:44.395
So, um...

53:49.617 --> 53:51.706
So, I don't... run away
from the world...

53:53.621 --> 53:55.188
Um...

54:10.159 --> 54:11.596
How do you get outta here?

54:11.639 --> 54:14.076
[laughing]

54:14.120 --> 54:15.513
Don't drink that.

54:17.515 --> 54:18.951
Here, let me have
some of that.

54:18.994 --> 54:20.605
It's very... jelly.

54:23.434 --> 54:25.305
Really?

54:25.349 --> 54:27.220
I think you're gonna like
what I have better.

54:27.264 --> 54:29.875
- [phone ringing]
- Hello, Bookstore.

54:29.918 --> 54:34.488
Hi, this is the Carol Robbins
auxiliary department.

54:34.532 --> 54:38.449
How can we...
help you, sir? Ma'am?

54:38.492 --> 54:40.407
Hello. Hello?

54:40.451 --> 54:42.366
Is there anyone there?
Is there anyone there?

54:42.409 --> 54:43.932
Is there anyone there?

54:45.282 --> 54:46.674
Carol, are you there?

54:46.718 --> 54:48.981
[laughing]

54:49.024 --> 54:51.288
Carol?

54:51.331 --> 54:53.551
Mrs. Antrobus.

54:53.594 --> 54:54.987
Becky Thatcher.

55:03.038 --> 55:04.605
[woman] Matt,
can we add two things?

55:04.649 --> 55:06.955
- Sure.
- Okay.

55:06.999 --> 55:10.481
Can we add
a manly bread book?

55:10.524 --> 55:12.483
- The-- which one?
- A breadmaking book

55:12.526 --> 55:16.269
that a guy who's just
getting into making bread

55:16.313 --> 55:18.315
- is gonna like.
- Huh. Okay.

55:19.577 --> 55:21.318
"In main lesson today,
we learned

55:21.361 --> 55:23.755
of the mighty conquest
of the great greenness,

55:23.798 --> 55:25.583
lord of all living things.

55:25.626 --> 55:28.020
How all things come and go.

55:28.063 --> 55:30.022
How love shines
from our brow

55:30.065 --> 55:33.286
if we have
died at least once.

55:33.330 --> 55:36.463
And are courageous
as dragonflies.

55:36.507 --> 55:40.511
And that is the only solution
to a world gone mad."

55:40.554 --> 55:43.122
[whispering]
One-three-nine-two...

55:43.165 --> 55:46.952
six-four-three-two...
seven-six-nine-one.

55:46.995 --> 55:51.783
Um... I want
the Mary Trump book.

55:51.826 --> 55:53.175
- Uh-huh.
- But I wanted to look

55:53.219 --> 55:56.004
and see what else
you had, so...

55:56.048 --> 55:57.745
I should have brought
the paper with me.

55:57.789 --> 56:00.835
- What?
- The Times.

56:00.879 --> 56:02.402
- The bestsellers.
- Oh.

56:02.446 --> 56:04.404
Let me go get you
a Times from last week.

56:04.448 --> 56:05.884
Okay, okay.

56:10.845 --> 56:13.108
[sighing]

56:13.152 --> 56:15.284
"In science,
extra main lesson today,

56:15.328 --> 56:17.286
we learned how vivid,
abundant,

56:17.330 --> 56:21.552
and wild blossoming is
in the highest places.

56:21.595 --> 56:24.163
How we sit around
a pond of knowledge,

56:24.206 --> 56:25.730
how we notice
at the edge of that pond,

56:25.773 --> 56:28.210
a shimmering chrysalis.

56:28.254 --> 56:31.562
How slowly, steadily,
the chrysalis molts,

56:31.605 --> 56:34.086
unfolds to recognition.

56:34.129 --> 56:36.610
How the young
dragonfly emerges,

56:36.654 --> 56:39.352
teeters on a blade of grass
testing its wings.

56:39.396 --> 56:42.964
How bravely, clumsily,
it tries to lift off.

56:43.008 --> 56:45.445
Often falling back,
but finally,

56:45.489 --> 56:48.753
finally, finally
into the meadow."

56:52.017 --> 56:54.411
- Hi.
- Hi.

56:54.454 --> 56:56.761
The world's oldest
and newest bookseller.

56:56.804 --> 57:02.419
Two weeks ago, I looked
at my bank statement.

57:04.203 --> 57:06.814
I looked at... what I have,
what the registers says

57:06.858 --> 57:12.472
that I have, and what...

57:12.516 --> 57:16.476
bills were coming due
at the end of the month.

57:16.520 --> 57:18.086
That was two weeks ago.

57:18.130 --> 57:21.046
I'm aware of...
of the...

57:26.312 --> 57:29.881
the place that
The Bookstore and I are in.

57:32.100 --> 57:33.885
It's a big love.

57:39.281 --> 57:40.892
Well...

57:40.935 --> 57:43.590
everything is informed by...

57:46.724 --> 57:48.987
kindness, patience,
generosity.

57:50.249 --> 57:51.642
I mean,
he's got time for it all.

57:51.685 --> 57:53.121
He's got time for everyone.

57:54.601 --> 57:56.342
Like, truly.

57:56.385 --> 57:58.083
That's been my experience.

57:58.126 --> 58:00.215
And it's been--
my favorite thing to do is

58:00.259 --> 58:02.261
to come in here
very anonymously

58:02.304 --> 58:03.784
and just walk
in the front door

58:03.828 --> 58:05.351
and sit in
one of the pink chairs

58:05.394 --> 58:06.613
and watch
his interaction with people

58:06.657 --> 58:08.136
here at the front desk.

58:13.533 --> 58:15.883
Because he knows
what the right thing to do is

58:15.927 --> 58:18.669
for The Bookstore.
It's always... it's in him.

58:18.712 --> 58:21.280
Because I... sort of
delude myself,

58:21.323 --> 58:24.805
and I'm like...
everything's great.

58:24.849 --> 58:28.069
Um... when I realized
that he was serious about this,

58:28.113 --> 58:31.899
I asked him,
"Is this... this is it?"

58:31.943 --> 58:33.510
Because I didn't know that--
that it was gonna be,

58:33.553 --> 58:35.294
"Save The Bookstore."

58:35.337 --> 58:36.948
I didn't--
maybe I didn't realize,

58:36.991 --> 58:38.340
maybe I've been so preoccupied
with my own stuff,

58:38.384 --> 58:40.255
but, I said, like,

